  "prompt": "Around what time did humans start naming each other?",
  "response": "The practice of naming each other among humans likely dates back to the earliest stages of human language development, which is thought to have begun around **50,000 to 100,000 years ago**. While it's impossible to pinpoint an exact time, the use of personal names would have emerged as language became more complex and social interactions required individual identification.\n\nEarly humans likely used names to distinguish individuals within their communities, for practical purposes like communication, social bonding, and establishing relationships. Names might have initially been simple descriptors (e.g., \"Tall One\" or \"Hunter\") and evolved into more specific and symbolic identifiers over time.\n\nEvidence of naming practices can be inferred from ancient cultures. For example, the earliest known recorded names appear in **Sumerian cuneiform texts** from around **3100 BCE**, and Egyptian hieroglyphs also contain personal names dating back to around **3000 BCE**.\n\nIn summary, the practice of naming each other likely began tens of thousands of years ago, evolving alongside human language and social structures.",
